Load Data

Read in the data.

data_url <- 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jyurko/CS_1675_Fall_2020/master/HW/final_project/cs_1675_final_project_data.csv'

df_raw <- readr::read_csv(data_url, col_names = TRUE)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   xA = col_character(),
##   xB = col_character(),
##   x01 = col_double(),
##   x02 = col_double(),
##   x03 = col_double(),
##   x04 = col_double(),
##   x05 = col_double(),
##   x06 = col_double(),
##   x07 = col_double(),
##   x08 = col_double(),
##   x09 = col_double(),
##   x10 = col_double(),
##   x11 = col_double(),
##   response_1 = col_double(),
##   outcome_2 = col_character()
## )

Separate the variables associated with Step 1.

df_step1_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, x01:x06, response_1)

Separate the variables associated with the Option B classification formulation. The outcome_2 variable is converted to a factor with a specific ordering of the levels. This ordering is used when modeling in caret to make sure everyone predicts the Fail class as the positive class in the confusion matrix.

df_step2_B_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, response_1, x07:x11, outcome_2) %>% 
  mutate(outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Separate the variables associated with the Option A classification formulation. The outcome_2 variable is again converted to a factor with a specific ordering of the levels.

df_step2_A_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, x01:x11, outcome_2) %>% 
  mutate(outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Change data types for the whole data frame to perform EDA.

df <- df_raw %>% 
  mutate(xA = as.factor(xA),
         xB = as.factor(xB),
         outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Standardize the data.

get_standardized <- function(df) {
  predict(preProcess(df, method = c('center', 'scale')), df) 
}

Load the best models

Summary.

Regression

  • eXtreme Gradient Boosting (tuned)

Option A

  • ROC: Random Forest (tuned)
  • Accuracy: eXtreme Gradient Boosting (tuned)

Option B

  • ROC: eXtreme Gradient Boosting (tuned)
  • Accuracy: eXtreme Gradient Boosting (tuned)

Regression

Describe.

eXtreme Gradient Boosting: the final values used for the model were nrounds = 100, max_depth = 6, eta = 0.1, gamma = 0, colsample_bytree = 0.8, min_child_weight = 1, and subsample = 1.

Functions to get the most important variables.

get_4_imp_vars <- function(model) {
  top_inputs <- (varImp(model))$importance %>%
    tibble::rownames_to_column('var_name') %>%
    arrange(desc(Overall)) %>%
    slice(1:4) %>%
    pull(var_name)
}
imp_var_threshold = 60

get_list_imp_vars <- function(model) {
  (varImp(model))$importance %>%
    tibble::rownames_to_column('var_name') %>%
    filter(Overall > imp_var_threshold) %>%
    pull(var_name)
}

Discussion - what model is ultimately the best

For both of the metrics (ROC and Accuracy), the best models were really close to each other in their performance. There is no definite way I am aware of to rate the complexity of the models in order to use the one standard rule to pick the best model; thus, when making my final choice for each of the metrics, I was choosing the best model based on the performance and uncertainty intervals. Mainly, I wanted the uncertainty interval to be as small to avoid the chances of getting a lower performance. Thus, the best models for both maximizing ROC and Accuracy were associated with option B. They were both tuned Gradient Boosted Trees.

  • ROC

eXtreme Gradient Boosting: the final values used for the model were nrounds = 20, max_depth = 5, eta = 0.2, gamma = 0, colsample_bytree = 0.8, min_child_weight = 1, and subsample = 1.

  • Accuracy

eXtreme Gradient Boosting: the final values used for the model were nrounds = 40, max_depth = 4, eta = 0.2, gamma = 0, colsample_bytree = 0.8, min_child_weight = 1, and subsample = 1.

Additionally, we have to remember that even though the models for option B were the best in performance, we have to also consider the models to estimate the response_1. Thus, in practice, it could be the case that option B models would perform worse because it requires more steps and you need to use different models to optimize for the inputs. However, for this assignment, I am choosing the best one more based on performance.

Now, to choose the best one from these two to use for optimization, we need to focus on the metric more. These model differ in 2 tuning parameters only: nrounds and max_depth. I think that I will go with ROC as the metric of choice because accuracy depends on the threshold chosen by the algorithm whereas AUC ROC takes into account all possible thresholds. Thus, I think that AUC ROC provides a broader view of the performance of the model compared to the accuracy. Although they do measure different things.

It is worth noting that tree-based models seemed to be superior for this problem for all the options with Gradient Boosted Tree being the best one. Although tuning the model matters a lot since the default Gradient Boosted Tree was not the best in any of the part of this final project. Other models that were close to it were Random Forest both default and tuned as well as tuned Neural Network. Generalize Additive model seem to perform good as well. However, LM and GLM, Elastic Net, and Partial Least Squares (PLS) seemed to be the worst ones across all the trials. PLS did not work well because it performs well with correlated inputs but the inputs for this problem were uncorrelated as we found out in the EDA part of the project and then proved by training the PLS models.

Define a function to help create the grid of input values.

Specify evenly spaced values between the min and max for the top inputs. All other inputs will be fixed at their median values.

make_input_grid <- function(var_name, top_input_names, all_data)
{
  xvar <- all_data %>% select(all_of(var_name)) %>% pull()
  
  if (var_name %in% top_input_names[1:2]){
    # use 25 unique values between the min/max values
    xgrid <- seq(min(xvar), max(xvar), length.out = 25)
  } else if (var_name %in% top_input_names[3:4]){
    # specify quantiles to use
    xgrid <- quantile(xvar, probs = c(0.05, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.95), na.rm = TRUE)
    xgrid <- as.vector(xgrid)
  } else {
    # set to their median values
    xgrid <- median(xvar, na.rm = TRUE)
  }  
  
  xgrid
}

What input settings are associated with minimizing the failure probability? Do the optimal input settings vary across discrete groups?

Based on the visualizations, I would recommend to set the inputs so that they match the yellow region. Thus, I would recommend to optimize the model for estimating the response_1 to get it to be somewhere in between 0 and -15, x08 to be within 78 and 80, x09 to be the highest so around 139, and last but not least, x07 to be within 143 - 145.

Discrete groups did not end up being the most important variables, so it is likely that the trends in the probability would not change if we vary discrete groups input values.
